  <body>
    <main class="page">
      <header class="hero">
        <a class="home-link" href="/" aria-label="Back to home">sokolsky.me</a>
        <p class="eyebrow">Book notes · Eric Berne, 1964</p>
        <h1>Games People Play</h1>
        <p class="dek">
          Eric Berne gave names to arguments that seem spontaneous but somehow
          always end in the same place.
        </p>
      </header>

      <article class="article">
        <section id="bottom-line" aria-labelledby="bottom-line-heading">
          <h2 id="bottom-line-heading">Bottom line</h2>
          <p>
            Berne thinks a lot of everyday friction follows a script. One person
            says something that sounds ordinary, a second message travels
            underneath it, and both people steer the conversation toward the
            same ending it always has. He calls the whole sequence a
            <em>game</em>. The prize is usually a bad feeling that confirms an
            old belief about the world—“Everybody wants to deprive me,” “People
            can’t be trusted,” “All men are tyrants,” “I am blameless.” Berne
            calls that belief the player’s <em>position</em>.
          </p>
          <p>
            I got less out of the game names than out of the sequences behind
            them. Once an argument starts to feel weirdly rehearsed, it helps to
            ignore the stated subject and watch what each person does to keep
            the argument going. Berne is far less convincing when he leaps from
            one memorable patient story to a sweeping claim about why people are
            the way they are.
          </p>
          <blockquote>
            <p>
              <em>The book is good at spotting loops. It is a poor excuse for
              diagnosing whoever annoyed you this week.</em>
            </p>
          </blockquote>
        </section>

        <section id="model" aria-labelledby="model-heading">
          <h2 id="model-heading">The model in five minutes</h2>
          <p>
            Berne’s building block is the <em>ego state</em>: three modes a
            person can operate in, each with its own feelings, vocabulary, tone
            and posture. Everyone has all three and switches between them, often
            mid-sentence. They are not ages or ranks—Berne insists “there is no
            such thing as an ‘immature person,’” only moments when the wrong
            mode is at the wheel.
          </p>
          <div class="ego-states" aria-label="The three ego states">
            <div class="ego-state">
              <p class="state-letter" aria-hidden="true">P</p>
              <h3>Parent</h3>
              <p>
                Your own parents, recorded. It scolds, protects and runs daily
                routine on autopilot (“that’s the way it’s done”)—useful for
                skipping a thousand small decisions, less useful when it nags in
                an inherited voice.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="ego-state">
              <p class="state-letter" aria-hidden="true">A</p>
              <h3>Adult</h3>
              <p>
                The part that deals with the here and now. It weighs facts and
                odds—when to cross a busy road—and referees between the other
                two.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="ego-state">
              <p class="state-letter" aria-hidden="true">C</p>
              <h3>Child</h3>
              <p>
                The child you once were, still in there. Home of intuition,
                play, charm and creativity—and of sulking, rebellion and the
                urge to please.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p>
            Conversation happens in <em>transactions</em>: one remark, one
            reply. “Do you know where my cuff links are?”—“On the desk.” An
            Adult question gets an Adult answer, and life moves on. But reply
            “You always blame me for everything!” and the exchange is
            <em>crossed</em>: a factual question got an answer from a hurt Child
            addressing an accusing Parent. The conversation derails, and the
            cuff links have to wait until the blame fight is over.
          </p>
          <p>
            A third kind is the engine of games: the <em>ulterior</em>
            transaction, which says one thing on the surface and another
            underneath. A salesman’s “This one is better, but you can’t afford
            it” is polite information on top and a dare underneath. The
            customer’s Child takes the dare: “That’s the one I’ll take.”
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="social-time" aria-labelledby="social-time-heading">
          <h2 id="social-time-heading">How people structure time</h2>
          <p>
            Berne starts from three hungers. People need stimulation, they need
            recognition, and they need something to do with their time. The
            recognition part runs on what he calls <em>strokes</em>: any act
            that says “I see you.” A nod is a stroke, a compliment is a stroke,
            and so is an insult. His running joke: “if you are not stroked, your
            spinal cord will shrivel up.” He points to experiments in which baby
            rats that were gently handled and baby rats that got electric shocks
            both did better than rats left alone. People work on the same grim
            math: painful attention beats no attention, and an insult can be had
            on demand, while affection has to be asked for and risked.
          </p>
          <p>
            So how do two people fill an hour together? Berne’s menu, from
            simplest to most demanding:
          </p>
          <ol class="ladder">
            <li>
              <strong>Rituals</strong>
              <span>Scripted exchanges everyone knows by heart: hello, how are you, fine, see you around. Berne scores the standard American greeting at exactly eight strokes.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Pastimes</strong>
              <span>Semi-scripted small talk on one subject—cars (“General Motors”), kids (“PTA”), clothes (“Wardrobe”). It fills time pleasantly, and it quietly auditions people as future game partners.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Games</strong>
              <span>Repeating exchanges with a hidden level and a payoff at the end.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Intimacy</strong>
              <span>Direct, honest contact with no hidden bargain. Berne calls it the only fully satisfying option—and the rarest.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Activity</strong>
              <span>Getting real work done together. The other four can all happen around a task.</span>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </section>

        <section id="anatomy" aria-labelledby="anatomy-heading">
          <h2 id="anatomy-heading">Anatomy of a game</h2>
          <p>
            Berne’s formal definition is a mouthful—“an ongoing series of
            complementary ulterior transactions progressing to a well-defined,
            predictable outcome.” In plain terms: a conversation with a hidden
            agenda that runs on rails toward a crash both people have been
            through before. What separates a game from a ritual or a pastime is
            that a game is “basically dishonest”—the stated subject is not the
            real one. And he is emphatic that these are unconscious habits, not
            deliberate cons. Most players have no idea a second level exists.
          </p>
          <div class="sequence" aria-label="Sequence of a psychological game">
            <div>
              <span>1</span>
              <p><strong>Con</strong><br />An opening move that looks straightforward but carries a hidden invitation.</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <span>2</span>
              <p><strong>Gimmick</strong><br />A weakness in the other person that makes them answer the hidden message.</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <span>3</span>
              <p><strong>Switch</strong><br />At a familiar cue, one player abruptly changes character and the friendly surface drops away.</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <span>4</span>
              <p><strong>Payoff</strong><br />A jolt of bad feeling that lands everyone exactly where they always end up.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p>
            The example in James R. Allen’s introduction to the modern edition:
            a mother finds a vase shattered, knows perfectly well the dog is
            outside, and still asks five-year-old Johnny, “Who did that?” The
            question is bait. “Doggie,” he says. Her neck reddens, the calm
            questioner vanishes, and she hits him: “I will not have a child who
            lies!” Her payoff is righteous fury—a round of “Now I’ve Got You.”
            His is feeling kicked. Had he said “I did it,” there would have been
            no game.
          </p>
          <p>
            Games survive because every player gets something out of them, even
            when the ending is miserable: attention, filled hours, an excuse to
            avoid something frightening and—always—fresh proof of that old
            childhood belief.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="games" aria-labelledby="games-heading">
          <h2 id="games-heading">The most useful games to recognize</h2>
          <div class="game-list">
            <article>
              <h3>Why Don’t You—Yes But</h3>
              <p>
                The game that started the whole theory—the first one Berne
                dissected. Someone presents a problem. Everyone offers
                solutions, and every solution gets a “Yes, but…” The point is
                not to collect ideas; it is to shoot them down. The payoff is
                the defeated silence when everyone finally gives up, which
                proves that nobody can help.
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Berne’s exit:</strong> don’t play adviser. “That is a difficult problem. What are you going to do about it?”</p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>If It Weren’t for You</h3>
              <p>
                The most common game between spouses. A wife complains that her
                controlling husband never lets her out—yet when therapy mellowed
                him and she signed up for dancing lessons, she discovered she
                was terrified of dance floors. The restriction she protests is
                one she chose, without knowing it, for protection.
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Berne’s exit:</strong> permissiveness. The game needs a “Don’t you dare”; a genuine “Go ahead!” exposes the fear.</p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>Now I’ve Got You, You Son of a Bitch</h3>
              <p>
                A plumber runs four dollars over an agreed quote on a
                four-hundred-dollar job, and the customer erupts with the stored
                fury of years. The four dollars is not the prize; the
                long-awaited license to prosecute is. The poker version: holding
                four aces and caring less about the pot than about having your
                opponent at your mercy.
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Berne’s exit:</strong> spell out terms up front, keep to them exactly, and when a genuine surprise comes up, yield gracefully instead of handing over the opening.</p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>See What You Made Me Do</h3>
              <p>
                A man absorbed in a task is interrupted by his wife or kid; the
                interruption “causes” his chisel to slip, and he wheels on the
                intruder in rage. The slip really came from his own irritation,
                and it did its job: the family learns to leave him alone. In
                the harder version he defers every decision to his wife, so
                whatever goes wrong is her fault: “You got me into this.”
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Berne’s exit:</strong> leave him alone when he wants to be alone—and hand decisions back instead of absorbing the blame for them.</p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>Kick Me</h3>
              <p>
                A man who behaves as if he wears a sign reading “Please Don’t
                Kick Me.” The temptation proves irresistible; when the kick duly
                arrives, he cries, “Why does this always happen to me?” If the
                people around him politely hold back, he pushes harder until
                somebody obliges.
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Exit:</strong> don’t kick—and look at the move he makes right before each predictable rejection.</p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>I’m Only Trying to Help You</h3>
              <p>
                A helper gives advice that fails, tries again, fails again—and
                is finally met with fury: “Look what you made me do!” His
                baffled hurt at the ingratitude is the payoff; it proves people
                are disappointing. Deep down, the last thing this helper needs
                is for the help to work.
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Berne’s exit:</strong> the honest version—“I think we can do something about it”—offered with no need for the other person to stay helpless.</p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>Schlemiel</h3>
              <p>
                A guest spills a drink on the hostess’s gown, burns the
                tablecloth with a cigarette, grinds gravy into the rug—and after
                each disaster says “I’m sorry.” The messes are fun, but the real
                payoff is the forgiveness squeezed out of the host every time.
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Berne’s exit:</strong> “Tonight you can wreck the rug—but please don’t say ‘I’m sorry.’”</p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>Blemish</h3>
              <p>
                The player privately feels “I am no good” and flips it outward
                into “They are no good.” He cannot relax around a new person
                until he finds the flaw—last year’s hat, hasn’t read Rilke. The
                find does double duty: it lifts his gloom and keeps the other
                person at a distance, where they can’t discover his flaws.
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Exit:</strong> notice when accurate criticism is doing the work of keeping someone safely dismissible.</p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>Uproar</h3>
              <p>
                Criticism answered with backtalk, voices rising, and it ends the
                way it always ends: with a slammed door. Berne’s classic case is
                a strict father and a teenage daughter. The nightly quarrel lets
                two people share a house while guaranteeing distance—the
                slammed doors emphasize the separate bedrooms.
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Exit:</strong> refuse the escalation. For these two, fighting is not a failure to get close; it is the method for staying apart.</p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>Wooden Leg</h3>
              <p>
                “What do you expect of a man with a wooden leg?” A real,
                exaggerated or invented limitation becomes a permanent excuse
                not to try; the courtroom version is the insanity plea. A
                well-read player can always find an expert to certify the
                excuse.
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Berne’s exit:</strong> “I don’t expect anything. The question is, what do you expect of yourself?”</p>
            </article>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section id="degrees" aria-labelledby="degrees-heading">
          <h2 id="degrees-heading">Not every game is equally serious</h2>
          <p>
            Berne grades games by how hard they are played. A first-degree game
            is fit for polite company. A second-degree game does no lasting
            damage, but the players would rather keep it private. A third-degree
            game is “played for keeps” and ends in the hospital, the courtroom
            or the morgue. His flirtation game “Rapo” runs the full scale:
            flirting for compliments at a party; leading a man on for the
            pleasure of rejecting him; and, at the extreme, a false accusation
            in court.
          </p>
          <p>
            Calling all three “patterns” can blur differences in harm. An awkward
            recurring conversation does not belong in the same category as abuse,
            addiction or violence.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="using-it" aria-labelledby="using-it-heading">
          <h2 id="using-it-heading">How to use the book without becoming unbearable</h2>
          <ul class="questions">
            <li>
              <strong>Start with your own payoff.</strong> Naming somebody else’s
              “game” is often just a sophisticated move in a new game.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Describe the sequence, not the person.</strong> “We reject
              every proposed solution” is more useful than “You’re playing Why
              Don’t You—Yes But.”
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Listen on both channels.</strong> What is being said
              openly? What response is being fished for underneath?
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Look for the switch.</strong> At what moment does a normal
              exchange turn into confusion, accusation or helplessness?
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Return to Adult.</strong> State the observable issue, ask a
              direct question and make responsibility explicit.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Offer a non-game alternative.</strong> A pattern weakens
              when the underlying need can be expressed without the trap.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="dated" aria-labelledby="dated-heading">
          <h2 id="dated-heading">What has not aged well</h2>
          <p>
            A lot of the book reads like 1964 because it is. Games are written
            up “from the male point of view unless they are clearly feminine,”
            and the feminine ones carry titles like “Frigid Woman” and “Harried”
            (the overloaded housewife), which Berne explains with penis envy.
            Homosexuality is treated as a game and a disorder. The “Alcoholic”
            chapter claims that “in game analysis there is no such thing as
            alcoholism”—only a role in a game—and that a real cure means the
            former Alcoholic “should be able to drink socially.” Modern
            addiction medicine says otherwise.
          </p>
          <p>
            Berne also generalizes freely from memorable cases. He floats the
            idea that schizophrenia may be a child’s desperate countermove to a
            family game, suggests games can help bring on asthma, and gives
            each game a tidy Freudian cause (“anal aggression,” “oral
            deprivation”). The sequences—the con, the switch, the payoff—are
            things a reader can genuinely watch for. His explanations of where
            they come from are mostly guesses, and the labels turn silly the
            moment they are treated as final answers.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="beyond" aria-labelledby="beyond-heading">
          <h2 id="beyond-heading">Beyond games</h2>
          <p>
            Berne calls the alternative <em>autonomy</em>. He breaks it into three
            capacities:
          </p>
          <dl class="autonomy">
            <div>
              <dt>Awareness</dt>
              <dd>“The capacity to see a coffeepot and hear the birds sing in one’s own way, and not the way one was taught.” Berne’s image is the commuter whose body is at the wheel while his mind is already at the office—awareness is being where you actually are.</dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt>Spontaneity</dt>
              <dd>The freedom to pick your response from everything you have—Parent, Adult and Child—instead of replaying the feeling you were trained to have.</dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt>Intimacy</dt>
              <dd>The open candor of an aware person: contact with no hidden agenda and no concealed bargain.</dd>
            </div>
          </dl>
          <p>
            Getting there, Berne says, amounts to “obtaining a friendly divorce
            from one’s parents… so that they may be agreeably visited on
            occasion, but are no longer dominant.” Parent and Child remain part
            of the person; autonomy means having some choice about who answers.
            He is not optimistic about the species—the closing chapter concedes
            that “there is no hope for the human race, but there is hope for
            individual members of it.”
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="sources" aria-labelledby="sources-heading">
          <h2 id="sources-heading">Sources and edition note</h2>
          <p>
            This summary is based on the 2011 Tantor eBook,
            <cite>Games People Play: The Basic Handbook of Transactional Analysis</cite>,
            which includes James R. Allen’s 2011 introduction and Kurt Vonnegut’s
            review from the June 11, 1965 issue of <cite>Life</cite>. All quotes
            are from that edition. I cross-checked publication details and
            terminology against the <a href="https://ericberne.com/games-people-play/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Eric Berne family site’s book guide</a>
            and its <a href="https://ericberne.com/transactional-analysis/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">introduction to transactional analysis</a>.
            Berne and his friends had to pool their money to get the book
            published in 1964; it became a runaway bestseller anyway.
          </p>
        </section>
      </article>
    </main>
  </body>
